        <title type="html"><![CDATA[simplify WritableStream example]]></title>
        <id>https://github.com/mdn/content/pull/38536</id>
        <link href="https://github.com/mdn/content/pull/38536"/>
        <updated>2025-03-14T01:03:31.000Z</updated>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<img src="https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/6856458?u=215e33360b9ddfee4db978bab8a275a39972aa9f&v=4" width="64" height="64" alt=""/><br/><h3 dir="auto">Description</h3>
<p dir="auto">The example is needlessly complex. It converts a string to a <code class="notranslate">Uint8Array</code>, then writes each byte of the array separately, and reconstructs the message later. It could simply send the string.  Streams are confusing enough. The examples shouldn't add to that.</p>
<h3 dir="auto">Motivation</h3>
<p dir="auto">I want developers to be able to understand essential concepts of streams and JavaScript clearly.</p>
<h3 dir="auto">Additional details</h3>
<p dir="auto">The example refers to the bytes within a <code class="notranslate">Uint8Array</code> as "chunks". They are just numbers. This is confusing. The confusion is eliminated by simply writing the message as a string to the stream.</p>]]></content>
